## Abstract

The prospect of self-improving artificial general intelligence (AGI) introduces a fundamental tension: recursive capability growth must be reconciled with alignment preservation, safety guarantees, and information-theoretic stability. This dissertation introduces the **Stable Recursive Intelligence (SRI)** framework, a mathematically rigorous model of continuous and discrete self-improvement dynamics constrained by geometric, informational, and control-theoretic principles. We formalize the **Maakoul constraint**, a requirement that mutual information between latent representations and rare environmental signals be non-decreasing throughout optimization, and prove that under five natural conditions—capability descent, Maakoul preservation, alignment invariance, verification-bounded updates, and control barrier safety—the resulting parameter trajectories exhibit monotonic capability growth, rare-signal retention, forward invariance of alignment subspaces, and strict safety. We bridge continuous flow dynamics to discrete stochastic updates, establishing supermartingale convergence and high-probability bounds on regressive proposals. The framework is instantiated in a toy latent-space agent, with empirical validation of all theoretical claims. This work provides the first unified theorem-level guarantee for recursive AGI self-improvement and opens a rigorous pathway toward verifiable, scalable alignment.

